2.4 DESeq2 import functions

Notes: - use different packages to produce desired outputs, along with the function that you need to use - tximport function, output: list of matrices - tximeta function, output: SummarizedExperiment - htseq-count function, output: files - featureCounts function, output: matrix - summarizeOverlaps function, output: SummarizedExperiment

library("pheatmap")
library("RColorBrewer")

Note: - must manually provide sampleDists to culstering_distance of pheatmap other pheatmap will assume matrix is the data values themselves and caluculate distances between rows/columns of distance matrix (not what is wanted)

sampleDistMatrix <- as.matrix(sampleDists)
rownames(sampleDistMatrix) <- paste(vsd$dex, vsd$cell, sep = " -  ")
colnames(sampleDistMatrix) <- NULL
colors <- colorRampPalette(rev(brewer.pal(9, "Blues")) ) (255)
pheatmap(sampleDistMatrix,
         clustering_distance_rows = sampleDists,
         clustering_distance_cols = sampleDists,
         col = colors)

  • can also calculate sample distances using Poisson Distance (PoiClaClu package)
library("PoiClaClu")
poisd <- PoissonDistance(t(counts(dds)))
samplePoisDistMatrix <- as.matrix( poisd$dd )
rownames(samplePoisDistMatrix) <- paste( dds$dex, dds$cell, sep=" - " )
colnames(samplePoisDistMatrix) <- NULL
pheatmap(samplePoisDistMatrix,
         clustering_distance_rows = poisd$dd,
         clustering_distance_cols = poisd$dd,
         col = colors)

4.5 PCA plot using Generalized PCA

Note: - can use generalized principal component analysis (GLM-PCA) to perform dimension reduction on data that’s not normally distributed

library("glmpca")

gpca <- glmpca(counts(dds), L = 2)
gpca.dat <- gpca$factors
gpca.dat$dex <- dds$dex
gpca.dat$cell <- dds$cell

ggplot(gpca.dat, aes(x = dim1, y = dim2, color = dex, shape = cell)) + 
  geom_point(size = 3) + coord_fixed() + ggtitle("glmpca - Generalized PCA")

4.6 MDS plot

Note: - multidimensional scaling (MDS) is useful when don’t have a matrix of data, but only a matrix of distances

mds <- as.data.frame(colData(vsd))  %>%
         cbind(cmdscale(sampleDistMatrix))
ggplot(mds, aes(x = `1`, y = `2`, color = dex, shape = cell)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) + coord_fixed() + ggtitle("MDS with VST data")

mdsPois <- as.data.frame(colData(dds)) %>%
   cbind(cmdscale(samplePoisDistMatrix))
ggplot(mdsPois, aes(x = `1`, y = `2`, color = dex, shape = cell)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) + coord_fixed() + ggtitle("MDS with PoissonDistances")

5 Differentiala expression analysis

5.1 Running differential expression pipeline

dds <- DESeq(dds)

8 Removing hidden batch effects

Notes: - can detect groupings of the samples using statistical methods designed for RNA-seq (sva package or RUVSeq package) - SVA package uses “surrogate variables” for the estimated variables that are wanted in analysis - RUV package uses “factors of unwanted variation” with “Remove Unwanted Variation” (RUV) - use SVA first to find hidden batch effects, then use RUV

8.1 Using SVA with DESeq2
